,Not Recommended,229580,17156058,"Posted: 21 July, 2015",all,Urisk,"Now that the game is only ten days away from its release I feel like I have to post a review just to communicate one vital piece of information that the developer of Dream fails to communicate to present and future customers:This game is listed as having ""VR Support"" - it does have the corresponding entry in the feature list.However this game only supports the Oculus Rift DK1. The official position of the developer is, that they will implement support for newer VR headmounted displays as soon as the engine they are using gets updated ... and that's the problem: This game was made in UDK. Epic, the developer of UDK, clearly stated that UDK won't get any updates EVER again. The developer of Dream knows this and is thus, by not removing the ""VR Support"" entry from the feature list, deliberately deceptive.The only positive thing that 'can' be said in this regard is, that the thread where I wrote about this problem months ago was not deleted or locked and I wasn't banned from the forums. So in some minimal regard they are better than some other developers of UDK games, who formerly planned to implement VR support, still want to use it as a selling point and actively suppress any statement of the impossibility of such VR support ever being implemented on their forums.For me however the fact that the VR support tag remains combined with the genre of this game (releasing a 1st person exploration game in this day and age means, that VR support is practically mendatory) is enough to not recommend Dream, as much as I'd like to give it a positive rating, since it 'seems' to be a nice game. I however cannot bring myself to play such a game on a normal monitor anymore."
