76561197968321754,Recommended,229580,17450285,"Posted: 8 August, 2015",all,Speedkillsuk,"Almost every other review is complaining about bugs, but I have a different problem: Howard. Every single word he utters is maddeningly pathetic. He's excruciatingly lame; a space where a personality should be. I eventually started to hope that the nightmares would consume him, because at least that would make him sort of interesting.So... why am I recommending this game? Because, amazingly, if you're able to look past a few bugs, a clunky interface, and the fact you're playing as Howard, then there's actually a genuinely interesting experience to be had here. The world design is seriously beautiful, and the puzzles are - for the most part - very well designed (if a bit on the easy side). Most importantly, the developers have done a fantastic job of translating dream experiences into meaningful gameplay mechanics and level design. Everything feels *almost* coherent, but constantly falling apart. Meaning always seems to be scattered around, just within your reach, but you can never quite grasp it. Symbols and items repeat themselves throughout each dream and nightmare in a semi-ordered yet mostly disjointed fashion. All of this is very well done, and generally leads to a great gaming approximation of dreaming.So yeah, despite its obvious flaws, it's a beautiful and unique experience which I'd heartily recommend... if you can forget you're playing as Howard."
