,Not Recommended,229580,19404390,"Posted: 30 November, 2015",all,Fireeye,"When I bought the game, I had the faint option of finding something similar to Yume Nikki or one of it's many fan tributes. As such, the fact that the game for the most part is a walking simulator where you sprint from A to B (and sprint you will) with only the occasional riddle or puzzle did not particularly bother me, and many parts of the game (such as a large park or a south sea resort built entire on offshore platforms) are nice enough to look at that you won't mind spending roughly half and hour simply running around in the place.Unfortunately, the developer's approach to the dreamworlds the player moves through is rather conservative, especially if you consider how you could put virtually anything into them. This becomes especially sad when you consider that many of the smaller ""side dreams"" actually tend to be way more interesting than the larger main levels. But safe for one side dream that looks as if straight ripped out of a McEscher painting and another more abstract area with looping corridors and warping tunnels, the infinite potential a veritable dream has in terms of design simply is not fully used. Instead, the game largely relies on fairly generic landscapes with the occasional out-of-place object thrown in to remind you that you are still dreaming.Add to this that the game's story is only seen in retroperspect, and that investigating the home of the player character for about ten minutes will tell you everything you need to know in order to predict the good and the bad ending,  and you will come to realize that the game simply lacks a strong source of motivation. You don't care about getting to know the story because you already know what happened and what will happen. You don't care about exploring new worlds because you expect them to be as bland as the first sand desert/ snow desert level. Even the music (which, for the record, is very well done) only keeps you going for so long.Long story short, Dream is a game that had an enormous amount of potential, but lost much of it due to design choices."
