76561197979282735,Not Recommended,229580,35249352,Posted: 27 September,all,[PSI] BC,"Full disclosure - I only played this game for an hour, and about a quarter of that was messing with the controls. Partly, this was down to control issues and basic mechanics; there is a major bug where if you try to bind certain keys to an action, the game will either not respond at all or will respond intermittently with no rhyme or reason. In some areas, jump is disabled, and even where it works, it often doesn't because the space you want to jump to is occupied by another of the invisible walls that infest the game world. The inventory system is also very difficult to get used to, jarring to look at (whatever you interact with floats next to a badly rendered hand with a beam of light connecting the hand to the object - am I holding these things with the force?), and inconsistent to interact with. Some items don't seem to do anything at all, and others do...something...but it's unclear what, if any, effect they have on the game. One time, I was in a dark place and kept selecting the flashlight over and over, but nothing happened. Turns out, you can't access items while swimming. Once I got out of the water, the light floated next to my hand...and still didn't light things up.The game also seems to have totally missed the memo that it's supposed to be a dream - the majority of the ""dream world"" seems quite real (at least the part I bothered to explore) and the character keeps reacting to it as if it is a real place, wondering aloud why a computer lab is in the middle of a desert, scoffing that the user left their password and login details right out in the open (why does a dream computer need a password, btw?), etc. Admittedly, a computer lab in a desert could be a dream-like juxtaposition, but not when there's a generator to power the machine and a post-it note for login details; that's just somebody putting a real computer in a very odd place for reasons that probably made sense to them.All these things were bad, but the real killer was that the whole thing is deadly dull - I wandered around the main character's house for several minutes before deciding there was nothing worth interacting with. Then I piloted the character to bed, which transitioned me to an equally dull and sterile 'dream world' full of cubes and objects that looked interactive but weren't, and then through a door to the desert. In the desert, there was a computer, and on the computer, there was a long file full of exposition that suggested some sort of upcoming action sequence with smoke creatures (but it also made them sound about as dangerous as a speeding ticket), but I couldn't get any of the commands listed on the computer to work, and after an interminable time wandering the desert in search of the labyrinth of scary smoke beings, I decided enough was enough.This game is full of bad design choices and bugs, and the story is about as engaging as an instruction manual for a stereo you don't own anymore, or maybe one of those ghastly work-orientation videos that tries to make learning fun. I can't actually think of anything nice to say about it, which is sad, because I definitely get the impression that somebody put a lot of work into this game. Sometimes passion and effort are enough to overcome lack of experience and even lack of talent, but not this time :("
